The rice portion could have been more generous given the cost of the entree. The cabbage was not my favorite. Recommation would be to ask to exchange the cabbage for extra rice. I did a take out order at  the establishment on Wacker PL. I usually don’t leave reviews especially a negative one but this order of oxtails and fried snapper with rice and beans with sides of cabbage and fried plantains has spurred me into action. The food lacks the authentic embodiment of Jamaican cooking. The rice was soft/mushy. The fish bland. The peppers, onions and carrots that was served with the fish was inedible because they tasted as if they were soaked in straight vinegar. The cabbage tasted as if it has been cooked over several times to the point of no return. The oxtails bland. The plantains were the only item that was not ruined. Who do they’ve cooking these food and passing it on as Jamaican cooking?! Just horrible. An order of $75 + got tossed in the trash. Save yourself the hassle and money.

I’m staying around the corner on business and found this gem in my search for a happy hour and some nibbles. I had a faaaabulous experience here! After living in the Caribbean I have high expectations for my island cuisine. Mr Brown’s definitely delivered. I had a legit rum punch with a true “Caribbean pour” (ok maybe more than one) and the jerk chicken dinner including peas and rice, cabbage, and plantain. It was delicious, authentic, and exactly what I hoped it would be. The service was excellent; friendly and fun and attentive. I told the owner if he wants to open a location out in Seattle where I live to please do so. :) Definitely stop in here. Oh, and their beef patty is spot on. Thanks for taking me back to my beloved BVI, Mr Brown’s!

My hubby and I were super excited to find this place specially because it served ox tail but were extremely underwhelmed and disappointed with the service. We sat down and decided to order and then the server told us that they are taking cash only. Which was a bit of an inconvenience since we didn’t plan for it, anyway we got cash, and then once we order food it was BAD!! Like microwaved food... oxtail was cold and not authentic at all... the wings were super dry and cold, the waffle fries were the only items hot but fried in bad oil, I have had better microwaved Jamaican patty than the one that was served here. Everything is super expensive for the quality of food and service offered. When the bill came we eventually ended up using our card, and it was a different server who picked it and this time the machine seemed to have no issues at all. So we wondered if the other guy was just trying to pocket cash from us. Anyway, I wouldn’t recommend this place... certainly not for an authentic Jamaican. The only thing good was the music playing here. Else for food, find a different spot.

Generally speaking I like Mr. Brown's Lounge but NOT a fan of this location. I prefer the location closer to Chicago Ave & Grand. The night we decided to visit this location (a group of 5) we stood at the front door for about 3 min before anyone decided to tell us that we can sit where ever we wanted (they weren't busy, maybe 3 tables were there). Then when we sat down, it took forever for someone to help us and when they did, it was a girl with a nasty attitude like we were bothering her or maybe she just hated her job. We didn't get everything we ordered and she just left and didn't bother telling us we would have a new waiter or anything. After a long while a guy came up and asked us if we needed anything else and then informed us that our waitress has left for the night and he would be taking care of us. I wish I remembered his name because he was the only person working that night that seemed to care about customers. We weren't planning to leave a tip for our original waitress, but he ended up getting a nice tip in the short amount of time he spent with us. I wouldn't go out of my way to go back to this location. Generally speaking the food, drinks and music at Mr. Brown's is usually pretty good, just go to the other location if you can.

If you're from Caribbean ancestry do not go here. I had a beef patty it wasn't even made fresh. It's like they pulled out a golden crust pattie and fried it. Smh. Who serves frozen patties in an authentic Caribbean restaurant?! They should be ashamed of themselves for that one. I had the jerk chicken. I will say the chicken tasted really good, like you'd expect.  However, they only give you one quarter of the container of rice and peas and it was dry and too spicy to enjoy.  The cabbage also didn't have salt. The staff were really nice. The ambience is reminiscent of a jamaican restaurant and the place is clean. Other than the kola champagne I had and the chicken I won't recommend this place for anything else. I'm still mad that the beef patties wasn't home made. Smdh. And they are pricy too for no reason. If the food was tasty I wouldn't mind the price but if you want authentic jamaican cuisine go elsewhere.
